label.value: abnormal proteolysis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which proteolysis is abnormal. Proteolysis is the hydrolysis of one or more peptide bonds within a protein.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished proteolysis during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the hydrolysis of peptide bonds within a protein does not occur. All proteolysis may be affected, or only cleavage of specific proteins, or even specific sites within specific proteins.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal spindle pole body organization

value.value: A cell phenotype in which spindle pole body organization is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Spindle pole body organization is a process that results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the spindle pole body (SPB).

label.value: normal spindle pole body

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the spindle pole bodies are normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) with respect to structure, composition, location, and orientation.

label.value: normal mitotic spindle pole body duplication

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mitotic spindle pole body duplication is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: asymmetric gamma-tubulin complex localization to single mitotic spindle pole body

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the gamma-tubulin complex is localized to only one spindle pole body instead of both.

definition.value: Note that this term has no connection to 'abnormal asymmetric protein localization to old or new mitotic spindle pole body' (FYPO:0001874), because that term refers to abnormalities in a process that normally results in asymmetric localization, whereas for the gamma-tubulin complex, symmetric localization to both SPBs is normal.

label.value: delayed exit from meiosis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which exit from meiosis begins later than normal.

label.value: normal duration of meiosis I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the duration of the first meiotic nuclear division is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: meiosis I metaphase/anaphase transition delay

value.value: A cell cycle phenotype in which the onset of anaphase of the first meiotic nuclear division begins later than normal.

label.value: abnormal cell cycle arrest in meiotic metaphase I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which progression through the first meiotic nuclear division (part of the meiotic cell cycle) is arrested in metaphase under conditions where arrest does not normally occur.

definition.value: Metaphase is defined as the part of mitosis when chromosomes are aligned in the middle of the spindle. If no spindle is present, do not use this term, but consider 'abnormal cell cycle arrest in mitotic prophase' (FYPO:0003145). Also do not use this term if the spindle has elongated at all. If the spindle has elongated, or you cannot tell whether a spindle is present, or metaphase cannot be clearly detected, annotate to the more general term 'abnormal cell cycle arrest in mitotic M phase' (FYPO:0000608). In cells that arrest in metaphase, chromosome separation does not occur.

label.value: decreased protein localization to chromatin at chromosome arms

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin along chromosome arms is decreased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased eukaryotic translation initiation factor 2B complex assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of eukaryotic translation initiation factor 2B complex assembly is decreased.

label.value: decreased number of Rad51 foci during cellular response to ionizing radiation

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of sites at which the protein Rad51 accumulates is lower than normal during a cellular response to ionizing radiation.

label.value: increased number of Rqh1 foci during cellular response to ionizing radiation

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of sites at which the protein Rqh1 accumulates is greater than normal during a cellular response to ionizing radiation.

label.value: increased punctate nuclear protein localization during cellular response to ionizing radiation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a protein that is normally localized to discrete regions in the nucleus, visible as foci or dots by microscopy, is abnormally localized such that more dots are observed than in normal (wild type) cells during a cellular response to ionizing radiation.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased DNA recombination during cellular response to ionizing radiation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of DNA recombination is increased during a cellular response to ionizing radiation.

label.value: normal DNA recombination frequency during cellular response to ionizing radiation

value.value: A regulation phenotype in which the frequency of DNA recombination is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during a cellular response to ionizing radiation.

label.value: progressively decreasing vegetative cell population growth rate

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is slower than normal, and the population growth rate decreases over successive generations.

label.value: progressively decreasing vegetative cell population growth rate followed by return to normal growth rate

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is slower than normal for several generations, with the population growth rate decreasing over successive generations, after which the population resumes growing at a normal or near-normal rate.

definition.value: This population growth pattern is often seen with mutations that affect telomere maintenance. The slowing growth reflects a high rate of cell death as telomeres shorten, and in a small sub-population of cells, chromosomes circularize allowing the population to resume growth at a higher, often normal, rate.

label.value: normal protein phosphorylation during cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during a cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to subtelomeric heterochromatin

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to subtelomeric heterochromatin is abolished.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal intracellular protein transport during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which protein transport in the cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal frequency of double-strand break repair via homologous recombination

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of double-strand break repair via homologous recombination is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: abolished double-strand break repair via homologous recombination

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which double-strand break repair via homologous recombination does not occur.

label.value: abnormal mitotic cell cycle regulation during cellular response to DNA double-strand break

value.value: A cellular response phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the regulation of the mitotic cell cycle in response to the presence of DNA double-strand breaks is abnormal.

label.value: increased protein level during mitotic G1 cell cycle arrest in response to nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell is higher than normal during arrest of the mitotic cell cycle in G1 phase due to nitrogen starvation. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal translation or abnormal regulation of translation, but note that changes in protein levels may result from changes in protein stability or degradation as well as changes in protein synthesis. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased telomeric 3' overhang length during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the single-stranded telomeric 3' overhang is longer than normal.

label.value: telomeric 3' overhang absent during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the single-stranded telomeric 3' overhang is not present. Total telomere length may be normal or abnormal.

label.value: telomeric regions absent from linear chromosomes

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which chromosomes remain linear, but lose telomeric repeats. Subtelomeric DNA may also be lost.

label.value: increased DNA recombination at telomere during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of DNA recombination is increased in telomeric regions.

definition.value: Note that this phenotype can be observed in haploid cells that have not undergone meiosis, sporulation and spore germination.

label.value: increased DNA recombination at telomere following meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of DNA recombination is increased in telomeric regions in haploid cells that have undergone meiosis, sporulation and spore germination.

label.value: increased DNA recombination at telomere during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of DNA recombination is increased in telomeric regions when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: Note that this phenotype can be observed in haploid cells that have not undergone meiosis, sporulation and spore germination.

label.value: decreased duration of mitotic S phase during cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the duration of progression through S phase of the mitotic cell cycle is shorter than normal during a cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate.

definition.value: Use this term if the duration of S phase is decreased relative to wild type cells exposed to MMS, no matter how the mutant S phase compares to S phase in untreated wild type cells.

label.value: normal protein level during cell cycle arrest in mitotic G1 phase in response to nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell that has arrested the mitotic cell cycle G1 phase in response to nitrogen starvation is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein degradation during mitosis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which protein degradation is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during mitosis. Protein degradation, also known as protein catabolism, is any metabolic process that results in the destruction of the native, active configuration of a protein, with or without the hydrolysis of peptide bonds.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased number of unattached kinetochores

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the attachment of spindle microtubules to the kinetochore results in a larger number of kinetochores remaining unattached than normal.

label.value: delayed onset of meiosis II

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the second meiotic nuclear division begins later than normal.

label.value: increased protein level during meiosis I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during the first meiotic nuclear division is higher than normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal translation or abnormal regulation of translation, but note that changes in protein levels may result from changes in protein stability or degradation as well as changes in protein synthesis. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein level during meiosis II

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during the second meiotic nuclear division is higher than normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal translation or abnormal regulation of translation, but note that changes in protein levels may result from changes in protein stability or degradation as well as changes in protein synthesis. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein level during meiotic anaphase I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during anaphase of the first meiotic nuclear division is higher than normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal translation or abnormal regulation of translation, but note that changes in protein levels may result from changes in protein stability or degradation as well as changes in protein synthesis. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein level during meiotic anaphase II

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during anaphase of the second meiotic nuclear division is higher than normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal translation or abnormal regulation of translation, but note that changes in protein levels may result from changes in protein stability or degradation as well as changes in protein synthesis. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: premature mitotic spindle elongation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which mitotic spindle elongation begins earlier than normal.

label.value: abolished ATPase activator activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which a gene product (usually a protein) that normally has ATPase activator activity has no activity in a mutant. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

definition.value: This term can be used for any ATPase activator activity that is abolished by a mutation, whether or not the mutated gene product normally acts as an ATPase activator.

label.value: abnormal mitochondrial crista morphology

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, or structure of the mitochondrial cristae is abnormal.

label.value: increased level of iron assimilation gene mRNA during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of one or more iron assimilation RNAs measured in a cell is higher than normal (i.e. higher than observed in wild-type cells). Iron assimilation RNAs are transcribed from genes whose products are involved in any process in which iron is solubilized and transported into a cell.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription.

label.value: inviable elongated cell with fragmented nucleus and mitotic cell cycle arrest in interphase during cellular response to UV

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetative cell is inviable and elongated, has a nucleus that is broken into multiple small fragments, and progression through the mitotic cell cycle is arrested in interphase during a cellular response to ultraviolet light. The cell contains no septum.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'inviable cell population' (FYPO:0002059) or one of its descendants.

label.value: decreased mitotic spindle microtubule depolymerization during mitotic anaphase A

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mitotic spindle microtubule depolymerization, i.e. the removal of tubulin dimers from a microtubule in the mitotic spindle, occurs to a lesser extent than normal during anaphase A.

label.value: decreased mitotic chromosome condensation during telophase

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mitotic chromosome condensation occurs to a lower extent than normal during telophase of mitosis.

label.value: curved elongated vegetative cell with long curved interphase microtubules

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetatively growing cell is elongated, is curved along the long axis, and contains cytoplasmic microtubules that are longer than normal and curved. In a curved cell, the long axis follows a smooth bend rather than a straight line.

definition.value: In these cells, cytoplasmic microtubules often become long enough to loop around the ends of the cell.

label.value: elongated C-shaped vegetative cell with long curved interphase microtubules

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetatively growing cell is elongated, is curved along the long axis to form a "C" shape, and contains cytoplasmic microtubules that are longer than normal and curved. In a curved cell, the long axis follows a smooth bend rather than a straight line. In a C-shaped cell, the curve is centered at the midpoint of the long axis of the cell. Microtubules curve around the ends of the cell and may become long enough to form loops.
